how people live their lives and perpetuate the cultural structures that produced a given form of shelter.The stories draw attention to colonial and missionary agendas, local and global economies, environmental disasters, cultural identities, social connections, and family continuity, as well as personal choices. And, as the chapter on homeless Hawaiians shows, even those without houses have stories to tell. Anthropologists, architects, environmental designers, geographers, and historians will welcome this diverse volume on a neglected yet important aspect of change in the lives of Pacific Islanders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHousingzPacific AreavCase studies. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aChowning, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDominy, Michèle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlinn, Juliana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFranco, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacpherson, Cluny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMageo Aga, Simeamativa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aModell, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRensel, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRensel, Jan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRodman Critchlow, Margaret, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRodman, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShaw, R. Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000